<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="3" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="3" pageNumber="18">
Arista thick with plumose pubescence. Mesoscutum with two small lateral spots and one large mid-posterior spot. Abdominal tergites 3-5 without short squamiform setae
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="19" start="start">.</pageBreakToken>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="19" type="specimen examined">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="19">Specimen examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="19">1 female, Taiwan, Jiayi, Shuisheliao (120.6595E, 23.6544N), 1165 m, 2010. XI. 16, Ding Yang. This specimen was collected from tropical forest by sweep net.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="19">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="19">China (Guangdong, Taiwan).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="19" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="19">This can be easily distinguished from other known species of the genus by the thick arista and unique marking pattern of the mesoscutum.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
